First, let's find the symmetric difference of A and B, denoted as A△B. The symmetric difference is the set of elements which are in either of the sets A or B, but not in their intersection.

A△B = (A ∪ B) - (A ∩ B)

A ∪ B = {p, q, r, s}
A ∩ B = {q, r}

A△B = {p, s}

Now, let's find the symmetric difference of B and A, denoted as B△A. Since the symmetric difference is commutative, B△A = A△B.

B△A = {p, s}

Now, let's evaluate the Cartesian product of (A△B) x (B△A):

(A△B) x (B△A) = ({p, s}) x ({p, s}) = {(p, p), (p, s), (s, p), (s, s)}

Now, let's find the Cartesian product of A x B and B x A:

A x B = {(p, q), (p, r), (p, s), (q, q), (q, r), (q, s), (r, q), (r, r), (r, s)}
B x A = {(q, p), (q, q), (q, r), (r, p), (r, q), (r, r), (s, p), (s, q), (s, r)}

Now, let's find the symmetric difference of (AxB) and (BxA):

(AxB) △ (BxA) = ({(p, q), (p, r), (p, s), (q, q), (q, r), (q, s), (r, q), (r, r), (r, s)}) △ ({(q, p), (q, q), (q, r), (r, p), (r, q), (r, r), (s, p), (s, q), (s, r)})

(AxB) △ (BxA) = {(p, q), (p, r), (p, s), (q, p), (q, r), (q, s), (r, p), (r, q), (r, s), (s, p), (s, q), (s, r)}

We can see that (A△B) x (B△A) = {(p, p), (p, s), (s, p), (s, s)} is not equal to (AxB) △ (BxA) = {(p, q), (p, r), (p, s), (q, p), (q, r), (q, s), (r, p), (r, q), (r, s), (s, p), (s, q), (s, r)}.
